<TEXT>
researchers reported today that abnormal nerve 
fibers extending into the brain appear in the noses of alzheimers 
victims which may permit scientists to study the illness in living 
nerve tissue for the first time 
the finding may also lead to the first definitive test for 
diagnosing alzheimers in a living patient said study coauthor 
barbara talamo 
alzheimer experts agreed that studying the nerve tissue may 
reveal secrets about the brain disease for which no cause or cure 
is known but they were skeptical that the tissue which can be 
removed under local anesthetic would be useful for a diagnostic 
test 
talamo is director of the neurosciences program at tufts medical 
school and associate professor of neurology and physiology at the 
school and the new england medical center both in boston 
she describes the new research in todays issue of the british 
journal nature with colleagues there and scientists from harvard 
medical school and the university of pennsylvania medical school 
alzheimers disease is a progressive degenerative illness that 
impairs memory thinking and behavior it afflicts an estimated 25 
million americans 
the new study focused on nerves found at the top of the nose 
within the inner lining where they are responsible for detecting 
odors the nerves extend threadlike projections into a portion of 
the brain that is affected by alzheimers disease talamo said 
researchers took nerve tissue samples from autopsies of nine 
alzheimers patients for comparison purposes they also sampled 
nasal tissue from autopsies of nine people of about the same ages 
but without similar disease and five people who had other brain 
diseases 
eight of the nine alzheimer samples showed marked production of 
nerve fibers called neurites that contained abnormal proteins the 
proteins were excessively modified by a chemical process called 
phosphorylation 
the proteins resembled those found in the brains of alzheimers 
patients in tangled structures within brain cells that are a 
hallmark of the disease talamo said 
in contrast samples from only two of the 14 comparison patients 
showed significant amounts of the abnormal fibers and a third 
showed a small amount 
those three people were among seven nonalzheimer subjects older 
than 65 noted david drachman of the university of massachusetts 
since the fibers appeared in three of the seven they may be 
present in many people older than 65 who do not have alzheimers he 
said that raises questions about the fibers usefulness in 
diagnosing the disease he said 
peter davies of the albert einstein college of medicine in bronx 
ny also said it is not known whether samples from living patients 
would be useful for diagnosis talamo said researchers plan to begin 
studies in living people 
drachman and davies did say that laboratory studies of nasal 
nerve tissue from alzheimer patients may help in learning about the 
disease but drachman said it depends on whether the tissue will 
show more convincing evidence that it reflects the alzheimers 
disease process 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890223-0008 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
the mere presence of more than 150 foreign 
delegations including some of the worlds top leaders for 
emperor hirohitos funeral is a testament to japans towering 
importance in the world 
yet the japanese themselves are not exactly secure with their 
status they take pride in their affluence but are also concerned 
over whether their nation is ready to be a world leader 
in fact national selfscrutiny wrought by the emperors death 
has spurred public debate over japans global responsibilities 
foreign relations and priorities for the 21st century 
government officials say japan intends to fulfill its role as a 
global economic power but is unprepared to be a world political 
leader or even a leader in asia preferring instead to follow the 
united states lead 
i think the japanese are embarrassed or confused when people 
speak of a leadership role because we are used to following so we 
are confused or lost makoto kuroda special adviser to the 
ministry of international trade and industry told a recent 
conference in tokyo 
we cant respond to demands from the united states and other 
countries because we havent discussed things among ourselves 
added commentator and business consultant kenichi ohmae we have 
to develop our point of view 
japan having made the leap from developing nation to economic 
superstar has become more active in international affairs in 
recent years but has kept to noncontroversial areas such as un 
peacekeeping activities and increasing aid to poor countries 
it also seeks to avoid antagonizing its asian neighbors who 
admire its economic progress but oppose a stronger japanese military 
the neighbors recall their treatment in world war ii when japan 
controlled the korean peninsula and much of china the south pacific 
and southeast asia 
japanese are still a subject of terror and suspicion for 
koreans even today said lee do hyang an editorial writer for 
chosun ilbo a seoul newspaper 
a 1987 japanese government survey showed sizable segments of 
southeast asia still see japan as a potential military threat of 
those polled 53 percent in thailand 47 percent in the philippines 
and 34 percent in malaysia said they thought japan could become a 
military power again 
growing trade inside asia has raised the possibility of a major 
trading bloc in asia led by japan that would compare with the 
european economic community and north america 
in the east asian region japan is seen to be a country playing 
a leadership role but i dont think japan has gone that far yet 
said toyoo gyohten vice minister of finance 
the united states which spends 65 percent of its total annual 
income on defense has urged japan which spends about 1 percent to 
do more to build up its own defenses 
but military spending is highly controversial here japans 
postwar constitution limits its military to defensive capabilities 
and bans deployment of soldiers overseas 
in a recent government poll 772 percent of the japanese 
surveyed disapproved of defense spending increases 
japan doesnt have the will or the capability to become a 
military power gyohten said 
tokyo views its international responsibility in mainly economic 
terms 
it has announced it will double its foreign aid to more than 50 
billion during a the five years ending in 1992 
in addition its 10 billion in aid in fiscal 1988 and a budgeted 
11 billion for 1989 have made it worlds largest donor to 
developing nations according to the parisbased organization of 
economic cooperation and development 
japan expects the united states to continue as the leader of 
noncommunist pacific rim nations gyoten said the question then 
is how can east asian countries achieve the role the united 
states wants them to play he said 
but many leading analysts say japan must formulate its own 
policies instead of following the lead of the united states and 
europe 
this passive approach is responsible for much of the criticism 
directed at japan hideo sato dean of the college of 
international relations at tsukuba university wrote in the japan 
economic journal 
yoshiro kurisaka of the japan institute for social and economic 
affairs contends that if japan does nothing but pursue its own 
economic interests it will recreate the nightmarish conditions 
that led to the pacific war 
i keenly feel that japans obligation to act with wisdom 
compassion and generosity will increase with the approach of the 
21st century he said in a recent arcticle 
</TEXT>
