<TEXT>
the latest update on the federal budget shows 
the deficit for the first four months of fiscal 1989 was smaller 
than during the comparable period a year earlier but analysts 
expect the good news wont last 
the treasury department reported wednesday that for the first 
four months of fiscal 1989 which began oct 1 the budget gap was 
648 billion 23 percent smaller than for the comparable period in 
fiscal 1988 
economists nevertheless expect the fiscal 1989 deficit to exceed 
the 1551 billion shortfall posted in 1988 as interest rates rise 
and the pace of spending increases 
the bush administration is projecting the deficit will hit 1633 
billion which would be a 53 percent increase from the level of red 
ink in fiscal 1988 
economist paul denoon of manufacturers hanover trust co in new 
york said the fiscal 1989 deficit is likely to be in the 160 
billion165 billion range 
as we get later in the year well start seeing some stronger 
outlay figures denoon said he said expenses associated with the 
financial failures in the savings and loan industry and rising 
interest rates will contribute to the larger deficit 
federal reserve chairman alan greenspan in congressional 
testimony this week indicated the central bank was likely to 
continue to push up interest rates in an effort to slow economic 
growth and thus restrain inflation 
worries about inflation were heightened by the release wednesday 
of the consumer price index for january which posted a 06 percent 
increase 
the government actually posted a 28 billion surplus in january 
due to a surge in revenue caused by quarterly tax payments from 
individuals 
government revenues reached 894 billion last month up 93 
percent from the same period a year earlier spending meanwhile 
was up 314 percent from january 1988 to 866 billion 
spending in january 1988 had been artificially low because social 
security checks which normally go out on the third day of that 
month were mailed out on dec 31 because of the new years holiday 
the change in benefits payments resulted in a 159 billion surplus 
in january 1988 
the biggest government spending categories last month were the 
military social security other programs in the department of 
health and human services interest on the national debt and farm 
subsidies 
military spending totaled 193 billion last month and 966 
billion for the past four months up 33 percent from the yearago 
period 
interest on the national debt totaled 159 billion in january 
and 842 billion for the first four months of the fiscal year up 
111 percent from a year earlier 
spending for social security was 18 billion in january and 726 
billion so far in the fiscal year up 57 percent from the 
comparable period in fiscal 1988 
other hhs programs including medicare and medicaid cost 135 
billion in january and 535 billion for the first four months of 
fiscal 1989 up 59 percent from the comparable period a year 
earlier 
spending by the agriculture department totaled 46 billion last 
month and 206 billion so far this fiscal year down 22 percent 
from a year earlier 
