<DOCNO> AP890223-0073 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
algerians voted today on a new 
constitution that would open the way to a multiparty system 
protect civil liberties and spell the end of two decades of 
socialism 
polling booths opened at 8 am for 12 hours of voting by this 
north african nations 13 million eligible voters who were casting 
ballots for the third time in less than four months 
voters overwhelmingly adopted a first set of political reforms in 
november and in december they reelected president chadli 
bendjedid 59 to a third fiveyear term 
bendjedids proposal to change the constitution is the highlight 
of a process of political and social reform under way since a week 
of bloody riots in october 
the unrest was largely blamed on the oilproducing nations 
struggling economy jolted by a world oil glut and straitjacketed by 
the oneparty socialist state 
while algerian voters are expected to overwhelmingly approve the 
constitution there have been only limited public calls on its 
behalf the ruling party has remained prudently silent 
islamic groups have been divided over the merits of the new 
document in an interview published wednesday in the daily horizons 
said ali belhadj a leader of a fundamentalist faction said if 
ethnic berbers communists and all the others have a voice 
algeria will become a field of ideological confrontations in 
contradictions with the beliefs of the algerian people 
the proposed constitution does not overtly authorize competing 
political parties to replace the ruling national liberation front 
currently the only legal political organization in this nation of 25 
million people but it does recognize the right to create 
associations of a political character 
it also guarantees freedom of expression and the right to strike 
within some limits 
the new constitution would restrict the power of the army to 
defending the national independence the unity and territorial 
integrity of the country 
under the current document the army had a role in the 
development of the country and the building of socialism 
also dropped is a declaration that the algerian state is 
socialist the new text contains no reference at all to socialism 
islam would remain the state religion and arabic the official 
language 
the proposed document would supercede the 1976 constitution drawn 
up under houari boumedienne marxist president from 196578 
for years bendjedid has quietly moved algeria away from orthodox 
socialism to a free market economy but has faced determined 
resistance from the ruling party and the government bureaucracy 
the october riots in which government offices were a main 
target quickened the process officials said 176 people died in the 
fighting but the figure was widely considered low 
a nov 3 referendum that dealt with the separation of powers 
between the president prime minister and national assembly or 
parliament was approved by 92 percent bendjedid was reelected 
dec 23 with 81 percent of the vote 
</TEXT>
