<TEXT>
abel wolman a johns hopkins university sanitary 
engineer who helped to bring safe drinking water to millions of 
people around the world has died at age 96 
wolman who died at his home wednesday collaborated 70 years ago 
with the late chemist linn h enslow to develop a method of 
purifying drinking water with precise amounts of chlorine 
its still the primary water treatment used today said jared 
l cohon vice provost for research at johns hopkins university 
its in use throughout the world thats a remarkable thing to 
say 
the concept of chlorinating water was not new when the two men 
developed their formula in 1918 but the technique had yet to be 
refined to take into account the bacterial content in a particular 
water source 
the formula specified how much chlorine should be mixed with a 
given source of water taking into consideration the bacterial 
content the acidity and other factors related to the waters 
desired taste and purity 
wolman had an unconventional willingness to discard western 
assumptions in his role as a cleanwater consultant to about 50 
countries his approach was to weigh unique aspects of each 
communitys water problems cultural barriers bureaucratic inertia 
and resistance to change 
he received the national medal of science from president ford in 
1975 in 1976 he shared the tyler ecology award a 150000 prize 
with two other scientists 
wolman was born in baltimore on june 10 1892 the fourth of six 
children of polish immigrants he received bachelors degrees in 
both arts and science from johns hopkins and joined the faculty in 
1921 in 1937 the university awarded him an honorary doctorate in 
engineering 
he advised the us public health service the tennessee valley 
authority the atomic energy commission and the world health 
organization 
wolman is survived by his son m gordon wolman chairman of the 
department of geography and environmental science at johns hopkins 
and four grandchildren 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

