<TEXT>
orders to factories for big ticket durable 
goods declined 3 percent in january the first decrease in four 
months and the biggest drop since last july the government report 
today 
the commerce department said demand for durable goods items 
expected to last three or more years totaled a seasonally adjusted 
12806 billion in january down from 13206 billion in december 
orders in virtually all major industry categories were down 
particularly in the volatile transportation and defense categories 
much of last months decline was due to a 72 percent fallback in 
transportation orders which had surged 221 percent in december due 
to high demand for aircraft and autos 
excluding transportation orders in all other categories were 
down 12 percent last month 
overall orders had been up a robust 73 percent in december the 
biggest increase since last june orders for all of 1988 had been up 
109 percent from 1987 the best showing since 1984 as 
manufacturers enjoyed an exportfueled rebound thanks to the decline 
of the dollar against foreign currencies 
januarys 3 percent decrease was the biggest decline since a 74 
percent drop last july and the first drop since a 28 percent 
decrease in september 
orders in the erratic defense category subject to wide swings 
depending on when government contracts are signed plunged 335 
percent in january after a 242 percent increase in december 
excluding defense all other orders were down 04 percent after 
rising 61 percent in december 
orders in the key category of nondefense capital goods 
considered a good sign of business intentions to modernize and 
expand were up 15 percent to 3996 billion last month the 
category had increased 99 percent in december 
in other industries orders for primary metals were down 12 
percent after a 44 percent jump in december 
orders for nonelectrical machinery were down 08 percent after a 
11 percent increase and orders for electrical machinery were down 
23 percent after falling 1 percent in december 
shipments of durable goods were unchanged in january at 12418 
billion following a 35 percent increase in december 
