from passengers and a videotape of the defendant standing near the 
hijacked plane at beirut airport the hijackers were demanding that 
palestinian guerrillas be removed from lebanon 
carter won tentative approval wednesday from us district judge 
aubrey e robinson to allow expert testimony concerning amal on 
condition that the defendant testify that he was ordered by his 
superiors to hijack an airplane 
if he testifies that he had a direct order we may allow it 
said robinson but he ruled out a defense based on the theory that 
all mechanisms of law and order had broken down in lebanon and that 
any reasonable person would have followed a command to hijack an 
airplane 
assistant us attorney ramsey johnson argued against allowing 
such testimony saying that the hijacking is so patently criminal 
that the defense of following orders should not be allowed in this 
case 
