<DOCNO> AP890223-0115 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
facts and figures on japan 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
territory an archipelego of volcanic origin four main islands 
and more than 3900 others off the east coast of the asian 
continent over twothirds mountainous total area is 151120 square 
miles about the size of montana 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
people seventhmost populous country with 122 million 
inhabitants 60 percent in urban areas koreans are the largest 
minority at 680000 aboriginal ainu number 24000 by official 
count up to 100000 by own estimates literacy rate 99 percent 35 
percent of high school graduates go to college 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
political system administrative power is vested in cabinet 
consisting of prime minister and 20 ministers postwar politics 
dominated by the ruling liberal democratic party parliament 
elected by secret ballot is the 512seat house of representatives 
and the 252seat house of councillors 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
imperial family the oldest hereditary monarchy in the world by 
legend dating from feb 11 660 bc and by historical accounts 
from the 5th century ad today the emperor is a constitutional 
monarch with ceremonial duties 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
economy worlds secondlargest after the united states with a 
gross national product of about 25 trillion in fiscal 1987 the 
growth rate for the period was 49 percent and per capita gnp 
reached 19642 unemployment is 25 percent the lowest in the 
industrial world because japan does not count defense personnel and 
those working more than one hour per week the trade surplus on 
customs clearance basis was 774 billion in calendar 1988 exports 
rose 156 percent in oneyear period to 265 billion in 1988 
imports climbed 254 percent to 1875 billion 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
agriculture main crops are rice other grains vegetables and 
fruit imports supply 67 percent of japans cereals 20 percent of 
its fruit and 22 percent of its meat 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
defense japans 29 billion defense budget in fiscal 1987 was 
1013 percent of gnp the allvolunteer self defense forces number 
more than 240000 and are strictly limited to a defensive role 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
religion buddhism is predominant with more than 30 million 
followers many also follow customs of the indigenous shinto faith 
which was devised into a state cult based around worship of the 
emperor for six decades until 1945 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
history records date back to 300 ad with the rise of yamato 
court in nara western japan by the midseventh century 
chinesestyle rule had been established incessant clan warfare 
prevailed from about 900 ad until the shogun tokugawa unified the 
country in 1603 and closed it off to the outside after the arrival 
of us ships in 1853 japan adopted a constitutional monarchy in 
1868 headed by emperor meiji as well as a europeanstyle 
bureaucracy and a military militarists expanded japanese rule in 
asia from the turn of the century until world war ii which ended 
with the us atomic bombing of hiroshima and nagasaki in august 
1945 us occupation forces dissolved japans familyrun financial 
combines purged military influence tried war criminals and 
introduced a democratic constitution the late emperor hirohito 
renounced his divine status after the wars end 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890223-0116 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
hans hellmut kirst one of west 
germanys most successful postwar novelists died thursday at the 
age of 74 
among his 46 books was the 1962 drama night of the generals 
which was made into a motion picture in hollywood 
kirsts works which were translated into 28 languages and sold 
more than 12 million copies worldwide focused on military life and 
modern historical events such as the july 20 1944 assassination 
attempt of adolf hitler 
born dec 5 1914 in the east prussian city of osterode kirst 
left school in 1933 to become a career soldier with hitlers army 
he served throughout world war ii and was imprisoned by us 
occupation forces after the fall of nazi germany 
he began his writing career in the late 1940s and gained 
prominence with his 0815 trilogy in the mid1950s 0815 is 
a military designation for basic recruits stemming from the name of 
a standard pistol issued to troops during world war i 
his honors included a 1965 edgar allen poe award and the knight 
of mark twain designation in 1968 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890223-0117 </DOCNO>
