because hirohitos death marked the end of the postwar era 
cbs coverage with more than 60 separate pieces to be broadcast 
over 18 hours is unprecedented because the network has taken its 
entire show on the road every news program except 60 minutes is 
broadcasting from japan cbs also scheduled live covering on its 
primetime program 48 hours 
the japanese always eager to learn how foreigners view them are 
busy drinking in the attention 
one japanese tv network is translating the cbs material and 
running them nightly and another network sent one of its anchors to 
los angeles to report on the us reaction to all the news about 
japan 
but the countrys week in the tv spotlight likely would not have 
happened if bush had not chosen japan as the site of his first 
overseas trip as president said lane venardos cbs executive 
producer for special events 
of course this is the dawn of a new era in japan and we felt 
that was worth reporting but george bush provides the catalyst for 
us to be here said venardos 
with feature stories ranging from memories of world war ii to 
sumo wrestling the risk is that people back in the us wont 
care and wont watch said venardos if its a turnoff we will 
have blown 2 million of cbs money and will be looking for new 
jobs 
long working hours attempts to drink in tokyos vibrant 
atmosphere and learn some of its rituals are taking a toll 
during a commercial on the set of cbs this morning host 
kathleen sullivan joked about a traditional tea ceremony she and 
cohost harry smith observed for the show 
the two had to kneel on the floor without moving for a 30minute 
rehearsal of the ceremony then repeat the excruciating halfhour 
for the real thing in introducing the spot sullivan sweetly read 
her lines coming up tea and serenity 
and pain she added through clenched teeth after the camera 
had clicked off 
cbs is not alone abc sent anchor peter jennings nbc sent anchor 
tom brokaw and cable news network sent mary alice williams and 
bernard shaw 
cbs started the week scooping the japanese media on their own 
turf with a 20minute interview with former prime minister yasuhiro 
nakasone in which nakasone made his first public statements denying 
any involvement in a stockprofiteering scandal that has rocked the 
government 
cnn sent a staff of more than 100 to tokyo to broadcast 20 hours 
of live coverage of the funeral and of the gathering of world 
leaders in tokyo 
nbc nightly news is broadcasting thursday and friday with 
brokaw at a serene japanesestyle garden at a tokyo tv station 
jennings is anchoring five nights of world news tonight from 
an outdoor post in the bustling commercial shibuya area of tokyo 
all four have been spotlighting japans culture economy and 
emerging political clout in reports leading up to the funeral and 
bushs activities 
