<TEXT>
the huge pressure vessel from the 
worlds first dismantled commercial nuclear reactor is awaiting 
better weather to begin its 8100mile journey through the panama 
canal to washington state for burial 
the 1000ton vessel and neutronshield tank from shippingport 
the nations first commercial nuclear plant were packed in concrete 
and lifted onto the 200foot seagoing barge paul bunyan in the ohio 
river last week 
the 60day journey to the us energy department dump at hanford 
wash will begin in several weeks when officials can count on 
better weather along its route down the ohio and mississippi rivers 
and through the gulf of mexico and pacific ocean department 
spokesman tom bauman said wednesday 
were going to make very sure its very safe for sea before we 
ship it he said there will be no danger whatsoever in fact 
the radioactivity levels are less than 1 percent of the standards 
allowed for this type of radioactive shipment 
the reactor vessel was hoisted from its underground site at 
shippingport 30 miles from pittsburgh on dec 14 in the most 
dramatic although not necesarily the most critical phase of the 
fiveyear decommissioning 
it was lifted by a crane placed on a specially constructed 
flatbed transporter with 320 rubber tires and rolled to the river 
bank and the barge which has a 4000ton capacity 
the shippingport plant was dedicated by president eisenhower in 
1957 and retired in 1982 after generating 65 billion kilowatthours 
of electricity 
it is the worlds only commercial reactor to be dismantled 
several nuclear plants have been mothballed or entombed 
the government hopes to show that reactors that have outlived 
their usefulness can be dismantled safely and affordably 
federal officials intend to remove all radioactive material so 
the site can be returned to unrestricted use no decision has been 
made as to how to use the land 
the decommissioning is expected to be completed by 1990 at a cost 
of about 98 million 
the cylindrical reactor 41 feet long 30 feet high and 18 feet 
in diameter is composed of a pressure vessel with 8inch steel 
walls and an encompassing neutron shield with steel walls 1 inches 
thick 
spaces within the assembly were filled with concrete to stabilize 
it and reduce radioactivity 
</TEXT>
