actor gene hackman says he blocked out most of 
his past including his anger at the father who abandoned him when 
he was 13 until his 1970 role in i never sang for my father 
the role of the estranged son opposite actor melvyn douglas 
prompted a reconciliation with the father who walked out on hackman 
his mother and his younger brother 
hackman said the resentment may have added to his macho image 
coming to terms with my fathers weakness made me understand 
that being strong means being honest hackman said in the upcoming 
issue of parade magazine 
hackman said that for a long time i did what a lot of 
successful people do which is to take credit for inventing oneself 
as if the past had nothing to do with it 
but then i saw myself becoming a frankenstein monster mouthing 
all the cliches of the socalled selfmade man like i pulled 
myself up by my bootstraps and ive paid my dues he said 
now hackman said i realize that its all part of who i am and 
that only by accepting everything i have experienced can i remain 
open to change 
