<TEXT>
william k reilly the new head of the 
environmental protection agency promised thursday vigorous 
enforcement of toxic waste cleanup cases saying a hard line is 
needed to force polluters to clean up sites voluntarily 
reilly said president bush has made clear in both public and 
private comments that he wants strong enforcement of the superfund 
law that provides 85 billion over five years for cleaning up toxic 
waste dumps 
but reilly in an interview with the associated press also said 
the cleanup effort will not succeed without voluntary action by many 
of the polluters 
i worry that we wont come close to making a dent in the 
national priority list of sites in need of cleanup in this century 
if we dont find some more creative ways to get people to settle 
their obligations said reilly 
as of last count the epa has listed 1175 toxic waste dumps as 
deserving priority for being cleaned up 
reilly the former head of the world wildlife fund and the first 
veteran environmentalist ever to head the epa said that while he 
strongly believes many environmental issues can be resolved through 
consensus he does not believe the superfund cleanup effort can 
succeed without government first wielding a big stick 
i think the problem with superfund is you want to create a 
climate of enforcement that is both certain and severe it needs 
an injection of vigorous enforcement to get the attention of people 
who wont come to the table said reilly 
the epas program aimed at cleaning up the nations toxic waste 
dumps has come under repeated criticism from congress and elsewhere 
over use of private consultants its level of compliance with 
timetables and its overall management 
reilly said that he too has concerns about the operation of the 
superfund program in recent years and has directed an internal 
examination of the program including a review of some two dozen 
reports and studies that have been done on the program by 
congressional investigators and others 
on other matters reilly reiterated that he is confident that 
bushs public promises to give environmental matters fresh priority 
are legitimate 
but he said budget constraints facing the federal government in 
general will also have an effect on the epa and the administrations 
ability to deal with environmental problems 
the budget deficit problem is serious that has got a high 
priority and leaves us with making due with less resources than we 
would like and that many programs need he said we need to be 
very creative 
</TEXT>
