<TEXT>
technology to completely clean up the most 
serious radioactive waste problems at the nations weapons plants 
does not yet exist a top official of the department of energy told 
a house subcommittee thursday 
troy wade acting assistant secretary for defense programs said 
the department was working to develop needed technology 
wade specifically said the department is still trying to find a 
way to deal with the aging singleshell underground tanks 
containing highly radioactive sludge at the hanford reservation in 
washington state 
over the past 40 years more than 500000 gallons of highly 
radioactive waste from the tanks have leaked into the soil at the 
reservation 
while the tanks are no longer in active use the department has 
yet to decide whether it will just pump out the remaining sludge and 
stabilize the tanks in place or whether an effort will be made to 
remove the tanks 
wades comments came shortly after the head of the general 
accounting office testified that hanford and other 
defenseproduction sites operated by the department may be 
irreversibly contaminated 
comptroller general charles bowsher who heads the investigative 
arm of congress also said he wasnt convinced that the department 
had the technical expertise to handle such problems 
some sites may be irreversibly contaminated and the department 
of energy may have to place them in longterm institutional care 
bowsher told the house energy and commerce committees 
transportation and hazardous materials subcommittee 
bowsher said that the departments weapons plants make up one 
of the more potentially dangerous industrial operations in the 
world and that to date none of the reports issued by the 
department adequately addresses the cleanup of the facilities 
does plan places modernization on a faster track than 
environmental cleanup and decontamination bowsher said 
