<TEXT>
the coldest air of the winter surged across the deep south on 
thursday icing highways and threatening the citrus harvest while 
delighting youngsters with rare snow and closed schools 
snowflakes reached the beaches on the gulf of mexico and 
temperatures dropped below freezing in northern florida 
meteorologists said traditional methods of keeping fruit crops from 
freezing might not help against the winddriven cold that pushed 
wind chill factors below zero across most of alabama 
businesses closed early in south carolina where gov carroll 
campbell also sent most state workers home in the middle of the 
afternoon one traffic death in georgia was blamed on icy roads 
elsewhere up to a foot of snow fell around the chicago area and 
northwestern indiana 
the core of the cold wave dropped temperatures to record lows 
across the midwest and as far south as tennessee and arkansas 
records included 17 at memphis tenn 2 at kansas city mo 13 
below zero at norfolk neb 13 below zero at spencer iowa and 10 
below zero at traverse city mich 
the combination of the cold and gusty wind produced wind chill 
readings of 11 degrees below zero at memphis naval air station in 
tennessee 14 below at harrison ark 22 below at springfield mo 
and zero at jackson miss 
lows early friday were predicted in the upper 20s in central 
florida and the high teens in the florida panhandle 
this is the coldest its going to be since january 1986 
said national weather service forecaster noel risnychok in coral 
gables fla 
the cold snap comes on the heels of record highs just last week 
that saw birmingham ala hit 78 twice 
flurries were reported in alabama as far south as mobile and 
baldwin counties on the gulf coast snow accumulated in northern 
alabama and sections of two interstate highways near trussville and 
