<TEXT>
the government friday pardoned 30000 people 
convicted of minor criminal offenses and restored civil rights to 
more than 11 million in commemoration of emperor hirohitos funeral 
the government this month announced plans to grant the amnesty 
which it has issued in the past to commemorate historical events 
the latest amnesties were issued in 1972 when the island of 
okinawa was returned to japan after 37 years of occupation by the 
united states 
government officials said about 10000 of the 30000 people 
pardoned friday were violators of the alien registraton law 
all but three people pardoned friday had completed their jail 
sentences officials said the amnesty will free this majority from 
criminal records 
the pardons also allow an additional 11 million people to recover 
such civil rights as the right to vote and run for public office 
which they had lost as a punishment for their offenses 
past amnesty plans included a much greater number of people a 
contoversial bribery and stock profiteering scandal facing 
politicians including members of prime minister noboru takeshitas 
cabinet forced the government not to include violators of bribery 
laws from those subject to the amnesty 
