<TEXT>
andrea marcovicci recalls a moment last year 
when she spotted a brief announcement that the american conservatory 
theatre would include george bernard shaws saint joan in its 
upcoming season 
marcovicci who was in town then to perform her cabaret act at 
the plush room turned to her accompanist and mused i wonder 
whos going to play st joan 
the surprise answer came when director michael smuin asked her to 
take on the title role which is sometimes described as the female 
equivalent of hamlet its won that reputation for three very good 
reasons first everybody who comes to see the play has their own 
vision of what joan of arc was like second the shavian concept of 
joan is quite unlike most others 
third almost every major actress of the 20th century has tried 
on joans sandals the leading women of stage have included uta 
hagen siobhan mckenna sarah miles joan plowright wendy hiller 
jane alexander lee grant and lynn redgrave ingrid bergman hedy 
lamar jean seberg and julie harris have played joan in screen 
adaptations 
being with such heavy talent is enough to cause any actor to lose 
sleep and marcovicci has indeed had trouble sleeping lately a 
month ago she was worried about learning her lines now she finds 
herself tossing in bed as she mentally walks through her part 
but she no longer worries whether shell measure up to the great 
performers of the past 
if you were to worry about that how could you ever get up if 
i were to think that way when i was singing it would be impossible 
for me to sing a song because ella fitzgerald did it so much better 
judy garland did the man that got away better than im ever going 
to do it so why should i ever try 
from what ive been reading ill never touch siobhan mckenna 
in their minds but then you have to throw that out and you have to 
say once you take on the part you become joan and she becomes 
you since she was a real person if you open yourself to the echoes 
of what she really said you should be able to take her on without 
too much intimidation 
marcovicci has retraced shaws footsteps in researching the part 
she has even read the transcript of joans nineweek trial which 
has shown her that shaw was correct when he told his admirers he was 
merely quoting the saint 
that transcript is staggering when you read it that great line 
when they say can you possibly tell me that you are in a state 
of grace and she says if i am not may god bring me to it if i 
am may god keep me in it thats exactly wordforword from 
the transcript 
marcovicci also wants to show another side of st joan 
i have to dare to let her be actually unpleasant at times 
which will be surprising to people who think well shes a saint 
and were supposed to love her at all times but she was irritating 
beyond belief to the people that were around her she said 
she allowed medals to be cast in her honor when she came into 
town she had the bells ringing a halfhour at a stretch so she 
could hear them she became quite puffed up thats the thing 
thats so tragic this really has shakespearean scope because she 
doesnt see what shes doing 
but marcovicci who played ophelia opposite sam waterstons 
hamlet at the new york shakespeare festival doesnt see the 
comparison of joan to the bards prince 
hamlet is much more difficult because hamlet is neurotic she 
said joan never doubted she firmly believed in everything she 
did because it came from god and she had what none of us have 
complete assurance 
although marcoviccis acting career has included roles in such 
shortlived musicals as ambassador chaplin and 
nefertiti and work in television and film she is best known to 
many as a torch singer and that strikes her as funny 
its weird ive only been best known as a singer in the last 
two years i mean people are coming up to me at my concert 
appearances and saying i heard a rumor you were once an actress 
after finishing the run of saint joan at act which opened 
feb 28 and will close april 7 she hopes to return to singing but 
marcovicci also intends to keep the public aware shes more than 
just another pretty soprano 
ive always wanted to go back to doing shakespeare she said 
id like to work again with joseph papp and i feel that this has 
opened that door again 
