<TEXT>
although its little known china has included 
jewish inhabitants going far back to the middle ages it later was 
home for thousands of them who fled nazism in europe 
most of them now live elsewhere but they plan a reunion this 
spring in that land where some have roots for generations and where 
others were given refuge 
at the time of hitlers rise when most countries had rejected 
them china opened its door to the refugees says yosef tekoah 
it was easier to find shelter there than elsewhere 
tekoah born and raised in china is now chancellor of ben gurion 
university of the negev in israel and that countrys former united 
nations ambassador he added in an interview 
many people in the west dont realize the greatness of chinese 
culture its inherent tolerance and humanity basically there was 
no discrimination of the kind which jewish people have suffered over 
the years in many countries 
as honorary chairman of an international assembly of jews in 
china to be held in shanghai april 1830 time of the jewish 
passover tekoah said it will be a significant event renewing 
old chinese ties 
it also will recall a part of jewish history an interesting 
and fascinating period in a great and fascinating country he 
said people are coming from all over the world 
the affair has implicit though unofficial approval of the 
chinese government planners say reflecting the thaw in 
chineseisraeli relations toward trade and other exchanges 
the earliest accounts of china jews go back before the journey of 
italian explorer marco polo into china in the l3th century the jews 
apparently having gone there from ancient israel or other parts of 
the middle east 
but traces of those olden china jews generally have disappeared 
over the years that community was completely assimilated and 
absorbed into chinese civilization tekoah said however here 
and there chinese people still claim they are descendents of that 
community 
he said remnants of it were reported in the centralnorthern part 
of china at kaifengfu near the end of the 19th century when 
christian missionaries first arrived in china 
there had been very little contact with china from the outside 
and the jewish community became isolated which is one reason it was 
completely absorbed he said 
however he said that at the same time about the end of the 19th 
century jewish families in india and iraq then both under british 
rule migrated to china including the kadouri hardoon and sasoon 
families 
they mostly settled in shanghai while in the early 20th century 
jews of european origin arrived especially russians fleeing the 
communist revolution and settling mainly in chinas manchurian 
north in harbin 
later they moved southward to mukden tientsin and shanghai 
which developed the largest jewish community in china a big influx 
from the nazi threat in germany poland and austria swelled 
shanghais jewish population to 20000 by 193839 
tekoahs forbears had left russia in the 1920s after the 
communist revolution and lived in harbin china where tekoah was 
born until 1937when the family moved south to shanghai 
most jewish people who have lived in china remember life there 
fondly he said china has one of the oldest civilizations in 
the world a very fascinating country 
jewish life there was quite developed with an advanced communal 
life organizationally there were synagogues schools elderly 
citizen homes newspapers and so forth 
however their residence there generally ended about 194849 as 
the nationalist government collapsed and the communist forces took 
over causing a general exodus of all westerners including jews 
some jewish people a very few remained into the 50s but 
they too soon left tekoah said his own family had left in 
1945 after which he completed undergraduate studies in the us 
before going on to israel 
shanghai buildings that had once housed jewish institutions have 
been converted to other purposes and signs of jewish life there 
removed 
however at the coming reunion there after 40 years of absence 
planners said that with the blessings of chinese authorities 
plaques are to be erected on sites cherished in jewish memory 
for most of us tekoah said returning to shanghai will be 
a tangible restatement of our faith in jewish survivial and our 
friendship toward china 
</TEXT>
