<TEXT>
a government report of a jump in inflation and a warning from the 
federal reserve about higher interest rates unnerved the stock and 
bond markets 
the labor department reported wednesday that consumer prices 
jumped 06 percent in january the fastest rise in two years and 
twice the 03 percent increases of november and december 
the government said prices rose not only in the volatile food and 
energy categories but also for a variety of other goods and 
services 
the latest increase translates to an annual inflation rate of 72 
percent in 1987 and 1988 inflation grew at a moderate 44 percent 
pace 
fed chairman alan greenspan pointed to the consumer price surge 
and restated an earlier warning that if price pressures are not 
brought under control inflation will advance and intensify a 
recession 
the fed has been trying to keep the economy from overheating by a 
series of credittightening moves that have pushed shortterm 
interest rates up about 3 percentage points since last march 
even in advance of wednesdays report worries about inflation 
were intensified by evidence that the economy entered 1989 with 
strong momentum and by a sharp 1 percent jump in wholesale prices 
during january 
economists predicted the fed would respond to the latest consumer 
price figures by swiftly driving interest rates even higher 
greenspan who testified for a second day before congress 
indicated the credit tightening would continue until the fed was 
satisfied the economy had slowed enough to lessen inflationary 
pressures 
on wall street the inflation numbers and greenspans remarks 
gave the dow jones average of 30 industrial stocks its worst day in 
three months the index skidded 4250 to 228393 while declining 
stocks outnumbered gainers by 4to1 on the new york stock exchange 
the credit markets also responded negatively to the news the 
treasurys closelywatched 30year bond fell about 625 for every 
1000 in face value its yield which moves in the opposite 
direction from its price jumped to 912 percent from late tuesdays 
905 percent 
gold and silver futures advanced modestly in reaction to the 
consumer price report 
president bushs chief economic adviser michael boskin said 
wednesday the administration believed inflation developments needed 
to be monitored closely with swift action taken if it appears that 
inflation is accelerating 
we will not tolerate a rise in inflation boskin said in an 
appearance before the joint economic committee of congress 
boskin stressed that it would be wrong to read too much into one 
months inflation figure 
in another report wednesday the government said it posted a 28 
billion surplus in january due to a surge in revenue caused by 
quarterly tax payments from individuals 
the treasury said government revenue totaled 894 billion last 
month up 93 percent from the same period a year earlier spending 
meanwhile was up 314 percent from january 1988 to 866 billion 
