<TEXT>
unisys corp which last week promised to 
trim its work force by 3 percent in 1989 has effectively met its 
goal by laying off 1700 employees at 60 us locations in a major 
restructuring 
in addition to the us layoffs the company said wednesday from 
its headquarters in suburban blue bell that it will close a 
component assembly plant in nogales mexico at a cost of 400 jobs 
obviously this is a major restructuring that has brought us 
essentially into the range where we told people we wanted to be for 
1989 said j peter hynes a unisys spokesman 
the move comes on the heels of last weeks announcement by unisys 
chairman w michael blumenthal that the computer giant planned to 
reduce its work force of 93000 by 3 percent this year or about 
2800 people and cut more than 500 million from its inventories by 
midyear 
about 190 employees at the companys headquarters were laid off 
wednesday and about 400 more will lose their jobs at the end of 
july when the company consolidates a computerdesign group at the 
headquarters with a larger division in roseville minn unisys said 
the action this week was just the latest move in unisys employee 
cutbacks 
since burroughs corps 48 billion takeover of sperry created 
unisys in 1986 the company has pared 18000 from its payroll 
through sales of operations and 12000 more through early 
retirements and layoffs not counting the layoffs announced 
wednesday 
hynes said only a small number of the affected employees 
would be transferred or rehired 
hynes said all employees released this week will receive six 
weeks pay in addition to a severance package all also are eligible 
for job counseling he said 
hynes said earlier that about 900 of unisys 68000 us 
employees have been offered early retirement so far this year 
on tuesday unisys introduced a longawaited line of mainframe 
computers designed by the engineering group in blue bell the new 
2200 series will replace the companys 1100 line the products 
release was delayed by several months hurting sales as customers 
postponed purchases until the new line was available 
blumenthal acknowledged last week that it had been a tougher 
year than anticipated and that he expected a weakness in sales to 
continue in the first half of 1989 
sales in 1988 increased 2 percent from 1987 to 99 billion 
although unisys profits rose about 18 percent in 1988 most of the 
increase was attributable to lower tax rates not bigger profit 
margins the companys operating profits slumped by nearly 
onequarter in the final quarter of 1988 
at a recent meeting with wall street analysts senior executives 
said they expected results from the first three months of 1989 to be 
poor with no revenue growth largely because of the bottoming 
of the 1100 product cycle 
the second quarter will improve as the new computer line starts 
kicking in revenue while the third and fourth quarters will be 
exceptional they said 
