a federal judge has refused to quash grand jury 
subpoenas issued to three traders in the probe of commodities 
trading practices ruling that it is too soon to decide questions 
about investigators methods 
attorneys for the traders contend their clients should not be 
forced to testify or hand over documents because evidence against 
them came from tape recordings obtained improperly by fbi 
investigators 
us district judge john grady rejected the argument in a ruling 
released wednesday attorneys for the traders who are identified 
only as john doe traders 1 and 2 and jane doe trader 1 said they 
would appeal 
the ruling was the first public document detailing legal 
maneuvers in the federal probe into suspected illegal trading 
activities at the chicago board of trade and chicago mercantile 
exchange 
grady said he couldnt rule on the propriety of the 
taperecordings unless he knew what questions prosecutors planned to 
ask the traders during grand jury proceedings 
it would be difficult to ascertain whether those questions are 
based upon electronic surveillance he wrote and if so 
whether they are based upon illegal as opposed to legal electronic 
surveillance 
grady placed a weeklong stay on subpoenas requiring the three 
traders to appear before the grand jury to allow them to appeal his 
ruling attorneys for the traders said they would appeal 
susan bogart who filed the motion for the traders said she was 
pleased grady recognizes the difficult and interesting question 
concerning the unlawfulness of the wiretaps 
