after a 22month investigation the state 
thursday fined six cooking oil wholesalers more than 1 million for 
allegedly diluting and mislabeling corn oil 
richard mcguire commissioner of the state agriculture and 
markets department said the companies mixed cheaper soy oil with 
corn oil and then labeled the products pure corn oil 
he said the state assessed 1021997 in penalties from the 
firms four of which are based in new york and two in new jersey 
the case of a seventh firm procter amp gamble co is being 
handled by state attorney general robert abrams mcguire said 
a state officials said the oil appeared on grocery store shelves 
under brand names and store brands but he didnt specify which ones 
state investigators conducted the oil probe by collecting samples 
from grocery stores and warehouses the state also subpoenaed 
records and officials of oil manufacturers and distributors mcguire 
said 
an analysis revealed widespread economic adulteration of corn 
oil he said 
soy oil is a fine healthy food product mcguire said the 
incentive for this fraud was purely economic at the time soy oil 
was considerably less expensive than corn oil 
the largest penalty 669007 was assessed to cbs food products 
corp of brooklyn manager bob green said the company will challenge 
the penalty 
