through the general assembly in less than one month winning its 
first committee approval on jan 31 clearing the senate on a 472 
vote and being approved by the house on a 935 vote 
sb 255 which is effective retroactively to the end of january 
expands on a section of indianas historic 1986 antitakeover law 
the measure states that boards of directors when considering 
buyout bids can weigh factors other than getting the topdollar 
price for shareholders the new law says that directors can also 
weigh the interests of constituents such as employees suppliers 
customers and the communities in which the companies are located 
i think its appropriate that the boards of directors take into 
account the interests of the people of indiana and not just the wall 
street brokers said bayh a democrat who took office jan 9 
indianas 1986 antitakeover law has been copied by other states 
since its adoption and a 1987 us supreme court decision upholding 
the law and a states attempt to protect its own companies 
however indianabased companies decided the 1986 statute needed 
strengthening after courts in delaware which has a similar law 
ruled last year that shareholders interest in getting the best 
return on their investments should be a boards primary standard in 
evaluating takeover bids 
the measure had the support of both cummins engine co and arvin 
industries two columbusbased corporations a british company 
currently owns almost 10 percent of cummins stock and an indonesian 
company announced recently it has purchased 56 percent of arvins 
stock 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

